Tap for Good Luck! Skibidi Toilet is a machinima web series of YouTube videos and shorts created by Alexey Gerasimov and uploaded on his YouTube channel DaFuq!?Boom!. Produced using Source Filmmaker, the series follows a fictional war between human-headed toilets and humanoid characters with electronic devices for heads. The series depicts a conflict between singing human-headed toilets—the titular “Skibidi Toilets”—and humanoids with CCTV cameras, speakers, and televisions in place of their heads. In a New York City-esque setting, the Skibidi Toilets, and their leader “G-Man” (canonically “G-toilet”[1]), threaten humanity.[2] Two types of humanoids, cameramen and speakermen, form an alliance against the toilets. Each has one of its kind that is much larger than the rest, termed “titans”. A toilet parasite infects the Speaker Titan, leading to casualties. Later in the series, TV-headed humanoids and their titan are introduced, and with their help, the speaker titan is broken free from mind control. The battle spreads to other cities, where the titans destroy what seems to be the G-Man, but is later revealed to be an impostor. The titans convene and seem to defeat the mastermind, the Scientist Toilet, but once again are fooled by a decoy. The true Scientist Toilet is revealed to be in hiding. After a strike mission, the Scientist Toilet is defeated, but all but one member of the crew are killed. The one remaining member is transported to meet the Secret Agent, a mysterious human seemingly involved in the creation of the toilets. Business Insider described the series as “an endless arms race as both the toilets and their foes [produce] stronger fighters”

Information about Tesla cybertruck The Tesla Cybertruck is an all-electric, battery-powered light-duty truck (LDT) that was unveiled by Tesla, Inc. in November 2019. Here are some key details: Design and Features: Exterior: The Cybertruck has a unique, futuristic design with sharp angles, a stainless steel exoskeleton, and armored glass windows. Its body is made from ultra-hard 30X cold-rolled stainless steel, which is said to be resistant to dents and corrosion. Interior: The interior of the Cybertruck is spacious and minimalistic, with a seating capacity for up to six people. It features a 17-inch touchscreen display, which is typical of Tesla's vehicles, and a dashboard made from a paper composite material. Storage: The Cybertruck has a large cargo bed, referred to as the "vault," which is 6.5 feet long and has a retractable cover. The vault offers 100 cubic feet of storage space, and there’s additional storage space under the bed and in the frunk (front trunk). Performance: Variants: The Cybertruck is expected to come in three configurations: Single Motor RWD: Rear-wheel drive with one motor, offering a range of around 250 miles, a 0-60 mph time of about 6.5 seconds, and a towing capacity of 7,500 pounds. Dual Motor AWD: All-wheel drive with two motors, offering a range of around 300 miles, a 0-60 mph time of about 4.5 seconds, and a towing capacity of 10,000 pounds. Tri-Motor AWD: All-wheel drive with three motors, offering a range of over 500 miles, a 0-60 mph time of about 2.9 seconds, and a towing capacity of 14,000 pounds. Technology: Autopilot: The Cybertruck is expected to come with Tesla’s Autopilot driver assistance system, with options for full self-driving capabilities. Adaptive Air Suspension: The truck will feature an adaptive air suspension system that allows for height adjustments to improve off-road capability or ease of loading. Toughened Glass: The windows are made of Tesla Armor Glass, which is intended to be much stronger than conventional glass. Price: The base model (Single Motor RWD) is expected to start at around $39,900. The Dual Motor AWD is expected to be priced around $49,900, while the Tri-Motor AWD version is expected to cost
